      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;Admittedly, I am a total newb at EQ, but I am an "old hand" at D2 and some other games.&amp;nbsp; I believe Frangellica and MadameRocks are on the right track here.&amp;nbsp; I love the idea of the epic quest, with occasional rewards along the way, as a way of getting players moving around.&amp;nbsp; And a few small adjustments, especially in drops, would help the lower-level newbs like me--especially when there are no others around to group with, and soloing is the only option--which is most of the time in the Neklutos Forest.&amp;nbsp; Maybe one of those higher-level players coming through Nek would even take the time to help me hunt down and stomp out the dreaded Leatherfoot Marshall.&amp;nbsp; As far as drops go, it wouldn't be hard to have an occasional "good, useable" drop that would not be overpowered.&amp;nbsp; Simply make the item dependent on level--not to use, as level restrictions are the worst thing that could possibly happen to EQ!&amp;nbsp; No, make the EFFECT dependent on level.&amp;nbsp; A random drop of a mace that has a base damage of, say, three, with a +1 damage per character level.&amp;nbsp; Or a breastplate with a base&amp;nbsp;AC of four, with a +1 bonus per level, etc.&amp;nbsp; The numbers I quote may not be balanced, as I have little experience at EQ, but with the correct balance it would work, and make some of those hard-earned items won by low-level chars worth hanging on to.&amp;nbsp; One little complaint--EQ is one stingy game!&amp;nbsp; It is bad to go up five full levels, selling everything that hits the ground--even prying the gold from all the orc's fillings!:smileysurprised:--and not have enough money to buy one chain shirt!:smileysad:&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
