    <item>
      <title>Re: Old school zones and low/no population.</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=TNZ&amp;message.id=169345#M169345</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;I did an analysis of this question many months (maybe even years) ago.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;It all comes down to cost vs. reward.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Cost includes such things as travel time, convenient places to sell off, bank and restock, danger of dying, difficulty of corpse runs, one-way pathing&amp;nbsp;etc.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Reward includes such obvious things as experience (particularly bonus experience), loot and general "fun factor".&amp;nbsp; And yes, risk is part of the "fun factor" so it can weigh on either side of the scales.&amp;nbsp; I think I speak for many of us when I say that some of our best memories are of those occasions when we "shouldn't have" prevailed, but nevertheless, somehow did.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;But there are non-obvious things such as, are there convenient places to sit and med, or are you at the risk of constant attack (e.g. Runnyeye)?&amp;nbsp; Is the mob level so spread out that those who can get experience from the low end mobs are at risk of getting creamed by the high end,&amp;nbsp;yet those who are at the high end have difficulty finding experience mobs (e.g. Dagnor's Cauldron)?&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Bear in mind also that as you progress forward through the expansions, mobs generally get more difficult.&amp;nbsp; They hit for more damage, have more hitpoints and/or have higher resistatnces, AC, etc.&amp;nbsp; So in terms of general ease, the "old world" is usually better, except of course for the zones which have been revamped and brought up to more "modern" standards.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;People will obviously go to a difficult dungeon if the reward is great enough.&amp;nbsp; Lower Guk is a particularly difficult dungeon crawl if you are level-appropriate, yet there used to be someone there all the time, camping the Rogue DE illusion mask, the Flowing Black Silk Sash, etc.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;With the old Splitpaw, it was rare to find anyone hunting beyond the "double doors", simply because of the difficulty of the dungeon with wanderers, see-invis casters and the one-way pathing.&amp;nbsp; Except for a couple of quests, there wasn't much to draw people in.&amp;nbsp; (I spent many happy hours playing in pre-revamp Splitpaw, so I think I know what I'm talking about.)&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;As a contrary example, the Warrens is a wonderful dungeon, because as you out-level the creatures near the entry, they ignore you and let you proceed unmolested into the deeper reaches, where you can find creatures to challenge your abilities.&amp;nbsp; (And of course the ones near the entrances will happily devour you if you get too low in hitpoints and attempt to flee, the fiends.)&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
